The '''Chrome OS core fonts''', also known as the '''Croscore fonts''', are a collection of three [[TrueType]] [[Typeface|font families]]: Arimo ([[sans-serif]]), Tinos ([[serif]]) and Cousine ([[monospaced font|monospace]]). These fonts are metrically compatible with [[Monotype Corporation]]’s [[Arial]], [[Times New Roman]], and [[Courier New]], the most commonly used fonts on Microsoft Windows operating system, for which they are intended as open-source substitutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Package: fonts-croscore|url=https://packages.debian.org/testing/fonts-croscore|website=Debian Packages|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=lwn-lib/>{{citation needed|reason=Who stated that these fonts are meant as a open-source substitutes|date=August 2017}}
[[Google]] licenses these fonts from [[Ascender Corporation]] under the [[Apache License|Apache License 2.0]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Fonts Arimo|url=https://www.google.com/fonts/specimen/Arimo|website=Google Fonts|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Google Fonts Tinos|url=https://www.google.com/fonts/specimen/Tinos|website=Google Fonts|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Google Fonts Cousine|url=https://www.google.com/fonts/specimen/Cousine|website=Google Fonts|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref>
The fonts were originally developed by [[Steve Matteson]] as Ascender Sans and Ascender Serif, and were also the basis for the [[Liberation fonts]] licensed by [[Red Hat]] under another open source license.<ref name=lwn-lib>Nathan Willis, [https://lwn.net/Articles/502371/ Liberation fonts and the tricky task of internationalization], LWN.net, 19 June 2012.</ref> In July 2012, version 2.0 of the Liberation fonts, based on the Croscore fonts, was released under the [[SIL Open Font License]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fedorahosted.org/liberation-fonts/|title=Overview - liberation-fonts - Pagure|website=Fedorahosted.org|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref>
The fonts are also available at [[Noto fonts]] repository at Github.<ref>{{cite web|title=noto-fonts/hinted at master|url=https://github.com/googlei18n/noto-fonts/tree/master/hinted|website=GitHub|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>
==Crosextra fonts== [[File:Calibri carlito comparison.png|thumb|A comparison between Calibri and Carlito in some of the more different glyphs.]] In 2013, Google released an additional Crosextra (Chrome OS Extra) package, featuring Carlito (which matches Microsoft's [[Calibri]]) and Caladea (matching [[Cambria (typeface)|Cambria]]). <ref>{{cite web|title=Substituting Calibri and Cambria Fonts - Debian Wiki|url=https://wiki.debian.org/SubstitutingCalibriAndCambriaFonts|website=Wiki.debian.org|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> These two fonts are respectively metric-adjusted versions of [[Lato (typeface)|Lato]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Greffrath|first1=Fabian|title=Debian -- Details of package fonts-crosextra-carlito in sid|url=https://packages.debian.org/sid/fonts-crosextra-carlito|website=Packages.debian.org|accessdate=11 October 2017|language=en}}</ref> and Cambo<ref>{{cite web|last1=Greffrath|first1=Fabian|title=Debian -- Details of package fonts-crosextra-caladea in sid|url=https://packages.debian.org/sid/fonts-crosextra-caladea|website=Packages.debian.org|accessdate=11 October 2017|language=en}}</ref>, both available on Google Fonts.
